/p></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p>Percentage change</p></td><td><p><strong>+0%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>+6%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>-1%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>-18%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>-1%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>-4%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>+20%</strong></p></td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>[h4] </strong><strong>Table notes</strong></p></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>(1) Excluding visitor and transit visas</p></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="8" rowspan="3"><p>(2) Student visitors are allowed to come to the UK for 6 months (or 11 months if they will be studying an English Language course) and cannot extend their stay. For consistency and comparability over time student visitor visas have been excluded from study-related totals.</p></td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td></tr><tr><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr></tbody></table><p>A copy of the latest release, “Immigration Statistics April to June 2015”, is available from the Library of the House and the Home Office website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</a></p><p>Similarly the Office for National Statistics figures on international migration to the UK (those changing their usual residence for 12 months or more) separately identify those whose main reason for migration is to study. The ONS figures are published as part of the Migration Statistics Quarterly Report, latest edition available at the following website and is attached to this answer: <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/migration1/migration-statistics-quarterly-report/august-2015/stb-msqr-august-2015.html" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/migration1/migration-statistics-quarterly-report/august-2015/stb-msqr-august-2015.html</a>.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-13T14:59:31.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419394/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419394/answer","Migration Statistics Quarterley Report August 2015.pdf","Migration Statistics Quarterley Report August 2015.pdf","Migration Statistics Quarterley report","Migration Statistics Quarterley report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419394/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-17","Immigration: Statistics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether distinguishing between overseas students and other migrants in published statistics would help to promote the United Kingdom as a destination for international students.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Dundee",,"The Earl of Dundee","HL2325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419395","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-01","<p>The Government values the contribution that international students make to the UK’s economy, and to making our education system one of the best in the world. According to the OECD’s Education at a Glance we remain, by some way, the second most popular destination in the world for international higher education students.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK India Education and Research Initiative (UKIERI) aims to enhance mutually beneficial educational links between India and the UK. Both Governments have agreed to continue this highly successful programme into a third phase to begin in 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>BIS has established a regular tripartite dialogue with colleagues from the Home Office and the Indian High Commission.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The British High Commission in Delhi (BHC) and the British Council in Delhi are also working hard to promote the message that the UK is open to all genuine students and that there is no limit on the number of international students who can study at our world leading universities. For example, through the GREAT campaign we have a strong digital and social media campaign with a focus on the employability of Indian students who have graduated from UK HEIs and on countering common visa myths.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2015-10-01T14:58:05.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419395/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419395/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of potential measures to reverse the recent decline in the number of overseas students coming to the United Kingdom to study or work, in particular those from India.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Dundee",,"The Earl of Dundee","HL2326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419396","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-30","<p>Overseas students are welcome in the UK and there is no cap on the number of such students. The OECD’s Education at a Glance, published annually, compares our performance with that of other countries. In 2012, the UK was estimated to have a 13% share of the international student market (OECD, 2014), second only to the US. The Government is committed to increasing education exports from £18bn in 2012 to £30bn by 2020and our International Education strategy is helping to achieve that.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2015-09-30T13:41:51.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419396/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419396/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how frequently, and in what way, they monitor and compare their performance in attracting overseas students to study and work in the United Kingdom with that of other countries; and following such analysis, whether they plan to make adjustments to their current policies.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Dundee",,"The Earl of Dundee","HL2327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419397","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-30","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Prior to 2012 international students who successfully completed a degree at a UK institution could apply for permission to work in the UK for two years. This Post-Study Work route was closed from 6th April 2012 as it granted unrestricted access to the UK labour market for two years to non-EEA nationals at a time when a large number of British graduates were unable to find work. The route was also found to be heavily abused with many people taking up low-skilled work rather than the intended graduate level roles. There are no plans to reintroduce this scheme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK has an excellent offer for overseas students graduating from UK universities wishing to remain in the UK. Those with an offer of a graduate-level job, paying a salary of at least £20,800, can take up sponsored employment for up to six years. In 2014 some 11,000 international students switched to skilled work. PhD students can stay in the UK for an extra year, under the Tier 4 Doctorate Extension Scheme, to look for work or start their own business. Graduate entrepreneurs can stay on for up to two years to develop their business in the UK. The Government has also made provisions for graduates wishing to undertake a period of professional training or a corporate internship related to their qualifications, before pursuing a career overseas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2015-09-30T13:41:29.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419397/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419397/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what comparisons they have made between their current and previous schemes to encourage foreign students to prolong their studies and take up employment with United Kingdom business and industry; and whether, as a result, they plan to amend their current scheme.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Dundee",,"The Earl of Dundee","HL2328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419398","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-01","<p>A breakdown of the Northern Ireland Executive’s Reinvestment and Reform Initiative (RRI) borrowing for the years 2003-2004 to 2014-15 is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2003-2004</p></td><td><p>2004-2005</p></td><td><p>2005-2006</p></td><td><p>2006-2007</p></td><td><p>2007-2008</p></td><td><p>2008-2009</p></td><td><p>2009-2010</p></td><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="12"><p>£million</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>79</p></td><td><p>169</p></td><td><p>163</p></td><td><p>206</p></td><td><p>105</p></td><td><p>260</p></td><td><p>246</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>375</p></td><td><p>151</p></td><td><p>196</p></td><td><p>259</p></td><td><p>2,409</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>So far this year, the Executive have drawn down £80 million of RRI borrowing. The maximum possible drawdown for 2015-16 is £327 million. Of that total, £100 million is additional capital borrowing provided by the Stormont House Agreement. Accessing this additional borrowing is dependent on continuing implementation of that Agreement.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL2330 ; HL2331","2015-10-01T14:57:32.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419398/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419398/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Northern Ireland Executive: Borrowing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the current amount of borrowing by the Northern Ireland Executive as a result of the Reinvestment and Reform Initiative.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419399","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-01","<p>A breakdown of the Northern Ireland Executive’s Reinvestment and Reform Initiative (RRI) borrowing for the years 2003-2004 to 2014-15 is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2003-2004</p></td><td><p>2004-2005</p></td><td><p>2005-2006</p></td><td><p>2006-2007</p></td><td><p>2007-2008</p></td><td><p>2008-2009</p></td><td><p>2009-2010</p></td><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="12"><p>£million</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>79</p></td><td><p>169</p></td><td><p>163</p></td><td><p>206</p></td><td><p>105</p></td><td><p>260</p></td><td><p>246</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>375</p></td><td><p>151</p></td><td><p>196</p></td><td><p>259</p></td><td><p>2,409</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>So far this year, the Executive have drawn down £80 million of RRI borrowing. The maximum possible drawdown for 2015-16 is £327 million. Of that total, £100 million is additional capital borrowing provided by the Stormont House Agreement. Accessing this additional borrowing is dependent on continuing implementation of that Agreement.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL2329 ; HL2331","2015-10-01T14:57:32.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419399/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419399/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Northern Ireland Executive: Borrowing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what they expect the amount of borrowing by the Northern Ireland Executive as a result of the Reinvestment and Reform Initiative to be by the end of 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419400","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-01","<p>A breakdown of the Northern Ireland Executive’s Reinvestment and Reform Initiative (RRI) borrowing for the years 2003-2004 to 2014-15 is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2003-2004</p></td><td><p>2004-2005</p></td><td><p>2005-2006</p></td><td><p>2006-2007</p></td><td><p>2007-2008</p></td><td><p>2008-2009</p></td><td><p>2009-2010</p></td><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="12"><p>£million</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>79</p></td><td><p>169</p></td><td><p>163</p></td><td><p>206</p></td><td><p>105</p></td><td><p>260</p></td><td><p>246</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>375</p></td><td><p>151</p></td><td><p>196</p></td><td><p>259</p></td><td><p>2,409</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>So far this year, the Executive have drawn down £80 million of RRI borrowing. The maximum possible drawdown for 2015-16 is £327 million. Of that total, £100 million is additional capital borrowing provided by the Stormont House Agreement. Accessing this additional borrowing is dependent on continuing implementation of that Agreement.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL2329 ; HL2330","2015-10-01T14:57:33.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419400/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419400/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Northern Ireland Executive: Borrowing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much borrowing has been incurred by the Northern Ireland Executive since the beginning of the Reinvestment and Reform Initiative, broken down by financial year.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419401","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>In September 2013 Severn River Crossing Plc (SRC) carried out major refurbishment of the movement joint and structural connection between the Wye Bridge and the Beachley Viaduct on the M48 Crossing. The estimated cost to SRC of this work is £0.75m.</p><p>Since 2006, SRC has been repainting the steel truss of the cable stayed bridge on the M4 Second Severn Crossing. This work is programmed to be completed before the end of the concession and to date the estimated cost to SRC is £5.1m</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-25T12:00:16.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419401/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419401/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","Severn River Crossing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the last major maintenance work was undertaken on the first and second Severn crossings, and what was the cost of that work.","false","Biography information for Lord German",,"Lord German","HL2332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419402","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>Severn River Crossing Plc (SRC) is required to maintain and repair both Severn Crossings. This includes performing regular maintenance and inspections work and carrying out any necessary repairs.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Separate maintenance costs are not available. The figures below for both crossings show all of SRC’s operational expenditure including maintenance on both crossings.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Operational expenditure (including maintenance) £m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>8.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>9.90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>10.62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>10.65</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>10.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>10.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>13.03</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>13.05</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>14.37</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>13.16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p /><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-25T11:26:36.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419402/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419402/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","Severn River Crossing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the annual cost of maintaining the first and second Severn crossings in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Lord German",,"Lord German","HL2333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419403","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-24","<p>EY’s 2014 report, ‘Getting Ready for UK Shale Gas: Supply chain and skills requirements and opportunities’ identifies that over the period of 2016–32 c.£33bn of spend could be required to bring up to 4,000 wells into production. At peak this equates to around £3.3bn of spend and some 64,500 jobs (6,100 of which are direct roles).</p><p>The full report can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="http://www.ey.com/Publication/vwLUAssets/Getting_ready_for_UK_shale_gas/$FILE/EY-Getting-ready-for-UK-shale-gas-April-2014.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.ey.com/Publication/vwLUAssets/Getting_ready_for_UK_shale_gas/$FILE/EY-Getting-ready-for-UK-shale-gas-April-2014.pdf</a></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-09-24T10:57:37.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419403/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419403/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-17","Fracking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by the Prime Minister on 11 September (HC9076), on what evidence they base the statement that "investment in shale could reach £33 billion and support 64,000 jobs in the oil, gas, construction, engineering and chemical sectors"; how many wells would be required to achieve such levels of investment and employment; and over what time period such levels would be achieved.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419404","Home Office","false","2015-10-05","<p>The response of the British public has been one of overwhelming generosity. In order to harness that response, the Government has established a webpage on gov.uk containing useful information on where to find further advice to frequently asked questions. The webpage has generated significant traffic in the last week, and aims to direct the public towards the most relevant information or bodies through which they can help, such as the Local Government Association website, or the websites of relevant charities and Non Governmental Associations. We are working closely with key partners to ensure that the offers received are captured by the appropriate organisation or body.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-05T16:43:41.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419404/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419404/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-17","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in relation to the webpages of the Communities and Local Government and Home Office sections of gov.uk entitled <i>Syria refugees: what you can do to help</i>, how many responses they have had in the first week from (1) the general public, (2) local authorities, (3) education providers, and (4) religious organisations, offering help under each of the headings; and what system they have set up for dealing with those responses.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419405","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-30","<p>The Department for Transport is allocating £1.3billion capital funding between 2015 and 2021 to local highway authorities that fall within the Northern Powerhouse for local highways maintenance. This funding can be used to repair potholes. The funding is not ring-fenced and it is entirely for each highway authority to decide, based on their needs and priorities, as to how this funding is spent. In addition the funding the Department for Transport allocated to local highway authorities in England to improve road conditions was £1 billion more over the last Parliament compared to what was provided between 2005 and 2010.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are able to use revenue funding for maintaining their local highways and this is allocated by the Department of Communities and Local Government through the Revenue Support Grant.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport is funding a local highways maintenance project in Sheffield as well as street lighting schemes in Blackpool, Knowsley, Leeds, Manchester, Newcastle, North Tyneside, Oldham, Redcar &amp; Cleveland, Rochdale, South Tyneside, Sunderland and Wakefield, through the Private Finance Initiative.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition we are also allocating £2.9 billion for improvements to the strategic road network within the Northern Powerhouse managed by Highways England as set out in the Road Investment Strategy published in March 2015 for the period between 2015 and 2020.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-30T13:53:35.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419405/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419405/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much of the funding allocated for the Northern Powerhouse will be spent on (1) repairs of potholes and damaged carriageways, and (2) other highway maintenance that would normally come out of annual revenue budgets; and how much of such spending will be allocated to (a) the Highways Agency, and (b) local highways authorities.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419406","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-30","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the written ministerial statements of 16 September, HLWS194 and HLWS195, which set out a number of measures to enable planning applications and appeals relating to shale gas and oil to be dealt with as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p>These include a commitment by the Secretary of State to actively consider calling-in shale planning applications. Separately, a scheme has been put in place to identify local planning authority underperformance in respect of their determination of oil and gas planning applications. The scheme uses the same threshold of underperformance set out in the document ‘Improving planning performance – Criteria for designation’, of 50% or fewer applications being made within the relevant statutory time limit, or such extended period as has been agreed in writing by the applicant. The statutory time limit applies once an application has been validated by the local planning authority. Where an authority is identified as underperforming under the scheme, the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government will actively consider calling-in for his determination oil and gas planning applications that are validated by that authority, in accordance with existing policy.</p><p> </p><p>The decision on whether to call-in any application will be taken in line with current call-in policy. Any applications relating to shale gas that are called-in would be prioritised for urgent resolution.</p><p> </p><p>If the Secretary of State were to grant a planning permission in respect of a called-in application, then any details of the scheme that are the subject of planning conditions would need to be submitted to and approved by the relevant local planning authority.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2338","2015-09-30T13:52:21.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419406/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419406/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-17","Fracking: Planning Permission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in considering whether to call in planning applications for schemes involving hydraulic fracturing that have taken longer than 16 weeks to be decided upon, they will count the 16 weeks from (1) the date the application was first received by the Minerals Planning Authority or (2) the date the application was registered; and whether, in either case, they will take into account (a) the timetable agreed between the applicant and the planning authority, even if that is for longer than 16 weeks, (b) delays caused by the failure of the applicant to provide the necessary information, (c) delays caused by defects in the application, (d) delays caused by amendments to the application, (e) an estimate of the additional costs likely to result from calling in the application, and (f) whether a call-in will result in a greater delay than allowing the planning authority to continue to deal with it.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419407","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-30","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the written ministerial statements of 16 September, HLWS194 and HLWS195, which set out a number of measures to enable planning applications and appeals relating to shale gas and oil to be dealt with as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p>These include a commitment by the Secretary of State to actively consider calling-in shale planning applications. Separately, a scheme has been put in place to identify local planning authority underperformance in respect of their determination of oil and gas planning applications. The scheme uses the same threshold of underperformance set out in the document ‘Improving planning performance – Criteria for designation’, of 50% or fewer applications being made within the relevant statutory time limit, or such extended period as has been agreed in writing by the applicant. The statutory time limit applies once an application has been validated by the local planning authority. Where an authority is identified as underperforming under the scheme, the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government will actively consider calling-in for his determination oil and gas planning applications that are validated by that authority, in accordance with existing policy.</p><p> </p><p>The decision on whether to call-in any application will be taken in line with current call-in policy. Any applications relating to shale gas that are called-in would be prioritised for urgent resolution.</p><p> </p><p>If the Secretary of State were to grant a planning permission in respect of a called-in application, then any details of the scheme that are the subject of planning conditions would need to be submitted to and approved by the relevant local planning authority.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2337","2015-09-30T13:52:20.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419407/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419407/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-17","Fracking: Planning Permission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the case of planning applications for schemes involving hydraulic fracturing that have been determined by the Secretary of State after being called in as a result of the failure of the Minerals Planning Authority to do so within 16 weeks, any conditions that require further approval of details of the scheme will be dealt with by application to (1) the planning authority, or (2) the Secretary of State.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419408","Home Office","false","2015-10-05","<p>Under international law the UK has a duty not to return people who are rescued at sea to countries where they would be at risk of serious harm. That is why migrants rescued at sea are taken to Italy as this is considered the nearest safe country.</p><p>But we are pushing for the swift establishment of 'hot spot' screening centres and action to return those who do not need our protection to their countries of origin.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-05T16:20:49.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419408/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419408/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-17","Refugees: Mediterranean Sea","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to take steps to ensure that the United Kingdom can decide where to land migrants rescued from the Mediterranean by the Royal Navy, so as to ensure that they are not landed in the European Union.","false","Biography information for Lord Higgins",,"Lord Higgins","HL2339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419409","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>Under the Sign up to Safety Scheme £8 Million has been awarded to 25 maternity units who submitted a successful bid to the National Health Service Litigation Authority incentivisation scheme. Most of the successful bids related to improvements in foetal monitoring (equipment and training) supervision, human factors and team working or a combination of these themes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All 51 bids (successful and unsuccessful) had to demonstrate a link to their claims. As such none of the bids made a specific reference to multiple births, the focus was on the causes within maternity that resulted in a particular injury outcome, for example resulting in brain damage</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A full evaluation of the impact of this scheme will be available next year.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T09:41:01.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419409/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419409/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Maternity Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the National Health Service Litigation Authority's Sign Up to Safety maternity-related projects include measures to improve the care of multiple pregnancies; and if so, when they expect to report the findings on those projects.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL2340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419410","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Maternity Safety Thermometer includes a function to allow staff to record whether the pregnancy in question was a singleton or multiple pregnancy. National Health Service providers who use the Maternity Safety Thermometer are therefore able to collect and use this information to drive improvements in care.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T10:18:04.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419410/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419410/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Maternity Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether NHS England’s Maternity Safety Thermometer will be updated to include a function to allow units to compare their data by (1) singleton, and (2) multiple, pregnancies; and if so, how they plan to use this information to drive improvements in care.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL2341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419411","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care in England. The CQC has advised that the responses to the national survey of National Health Service maternity services are currently being collated and analysed. Until all of this data has been analysed it is not possible for the CQC to comment on what will be included in the final report.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T09:39:39.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419411/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419411/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Maternity Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Care Quality Commission’s final report outlining the findings of their national maternity survey will include a specific summary setting out the experience of multiple birth mothers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL2342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419412","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The majority of the conditions such as Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder, Attention Deficit Disorder, cerebral palsy and speech and language delays identified in the question would only become apparent later in life. The Hospital Episode Statistics, which are collected by Health and Social Care Information Centre does not hold this data.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There has been no assessment made of the cost to families or public services of the implications of these conditions in multiple pregnancies.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T09:43:28.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419412/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419412/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Multiple Births","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of multiple pregnancies result in one or more babies with (1) Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder, (2) Attention Deficit Disorder, (3) cerebral palsy, and (4) speech and language delays; and what estimate they have made of the additional costs to families and public services in addressing each of those needs.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL2343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419413","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Government has been clear that it wants to engage and harness a wider range of expertise as part of the 2015 Spending Review process and accordingly welcomes the submission of the Nuffield Trust.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Rising demands and continued fiscal constraint means that the National Health Service faces challenges in ensuring that it remains financially sustainable in the future. The Government believes that the answer to these challenges lies in changing the way services are delivered and keeping people well and independent for longer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This is why the Government has committed to fully meeting the additional funding requirement – £8 billion per year over and above inflation by 2020-21 – identified by the NHS Five Year Forward View.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T13:12:32.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419413/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419413/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","NHS: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what account they are taking of the submission by the Nuffield Trust on National Health Service funding in the 2015 Comprehensive Spending Review.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419414","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, leadership experience and stability are an important factor in running successful National Health Service organisations. This is precisely why one of the new functions of NHS Improvement, working with other organisations such as Health Education England, will be to create and support the new generation of NHS leaders.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T09:41:43.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419414/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419414/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","NHS: Managers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the most recent annual figure for the turnover of chief executives of National Health Service organisations.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419415","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>This information is not collected or held centrally.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T09:41:10.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419415/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419415/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","NHS: Managers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the average length of tenure of chief executives in the National Health Service.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419416","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>This information is not held centrally by the Department.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T10:32:43.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419416/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419416/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","NHS: Managers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many National Health Service organisations currently have vacancies for chief executive posts.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419417","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) advises Ministers and the National Health Service in all four countries about all aspects of screening policy and supports implementation based on the best available evidence.</p><p> </p><p><br> Bowel cancer screening by Faecal Occult Blood testing for men and women aged 50-74 was recommended by the UK NSC in July 2003. Following this recommendation, the NHS Bowel Cancer Screening Programme in England initially invited men and women aged 60-69 years old as the programme was rolled out across the country. This has now been extended to men and women aged up to 74, as recommended in the Cancer Reform Strategy (2007). The programme offers screening up to the age of 74 based on the original English<sup>1</sup> and Danish<sup>2</sup> trials along with evidence published in 2010 (Cairns et al, 2010) which recommended that surveillance seizes at the age of 75.</p><p> </p><p><br> No assessment has been made regarding automatically inviting those over 75 years for bowel screening. Men and women aged above the eligible age limit have been able to self-refer for screening every two years since the programme began, and so far over 150,000 have done so.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>Hardcastle JD, Chamberlain JO, Robinson MH, Moss SM, Amar SS, Balfour TW, James PD, Mangham CM. Randomised controlled trial of faecal-occult-blood screening for colorectal cancer.</p><p> </p><p>Lancet. 1996:348(9040);1472-7</p><p> </p><p>2 Kronborg O, Fenger C, Olsen J, Jorgensen OD, Sondergaard O. Randomised study of screening for colorectal cancer with faecal-occult-blood test.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T13:09:43.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419417/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419417/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Bowel Cancer: Screening","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why people who have reached the age of 75 are not automatically invited for a bowel screening to identify symptoms of bowel cancer.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419418","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) advises Ministers and the National Health Service in all four countries about all aspects of screening policy and supports implementation based on the best available evidence.</p><p> </p><p><br> Bowel cancer screening by Faecal Occult Blood testing for men and women aged 50-74 was recommended by the UK NSC in July 2003. Following this recommendation, the NHS Bowel Cancer Screening Programme in England initially invited men and women aged 60-69 years old as the programme was rolled out across the country. This has now been extended to men and women aged up to 74, as recommended in the Cancer Reform Strategy (2007). The programme offers screening up to the age of 74 based on the original English<sup>1</sup> and Danish<sup>2</sup> trials along with evidence published in 2010 (Cairns et al, 2010) which recommended that surveillance seizes at the age of 75.</p><p> </p><p><br> No assessment has been made regarding automatically inviting those over 75 years for bowel screening. Men and women aged above the eligible age limit have been able to self-refer for screening every two years since the programme began, and so far over 150,000 have done so.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>Hardcastle JD, Chamberlain JO, Robinson MH, Moss SM, Amar SS, Balfour TW, James PD, Mangham CM. Randomised controlled trial of faecal-occult-blood screening for colorectal cancer.</p><p> </p><p>Lancet. 1996:348(9040);1472-7</p><p> </p><p><sup>2</sup>Kronborg O, Fenger C, Olsen J, Jorgensen OD, Sondergaard O. Randomised study of screening for colorectal cancer with faecal-occult-blood test.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-09-22T15:26:42.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419418/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419418/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Bowel Cancer: Screening","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether not automatically inviting those aged 75 or over for a bowel screening test complies with their duties under the Equalities Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419419","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-09-23","<p>The Parades Commission is responsible for the management of its own budget and, in line with the Public Processions Act (NI) 1998, it is also responsible for the publication of its Annual Report and Accounts. The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland is responsible for ensuring that the annual report is laid in Parliament. The total expenditure for the Parades Commission for each year since its establishment in 1998 is listed below:</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Financial Year (£000s)</strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2015/16 810 (projected)</p><p> </p><p>2014/15 969</p><p> </p><p>2013/14 916</p><p> </p><p>2012/13 1,373</p><p> </p><p>2011/12 958</p><p> </p><p>2010/11 1,023</p><p> </p><p>2009/10 1,032</p><p> </p><p>2008/09 1,130</p><p> </p><p>2007/08 1,062</p><p> </p><p>2006/07 1,740</p><p> </p><p>2005/06 1,460</p><p> </p><p>2004/05 1,166</p><p> </p><p>2003/04 1,292</p><p> </p><p>2002/03 1,296</p><p> </p><p>2001/02 1,308</p><p> </p><p>2000/01 1,138</p><p> </p><p>1999/2000 1,055</p><p> </p><p>1998/99 1,147</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-09-23T15:35:31.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419419/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419419/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-09-17","Parades Commission: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what has been the amount of each year’s budget for the Northern Ireland Parades Commission since its establishment.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419420","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-09-23","<p>This Government has had no discussions with the Parades Commission for Northern Ireland regarding the disclosure of evidence received, or on any other factors which are into account when making determinations.</p><p>This is an operational matter for the Commission acting independently of Government.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-09-23T15:35:43.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419420/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419420/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-09-17","Parades Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have discussed, or plan to discuss, with the Northern Ireland Parades Commission the case for making public, along with each decision it makes, (1) a full disclosure of evidence received, including from whom it was received, and (2) all other factors involved in the Commission’s determination; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419421","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>The number of ships over 100 GT on the UK register in 2005 and to date are detailed below. All totals were correct at 31st December in the respective year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>December 2005 1,438</p><p> </p><p>December 2006 1,456</p><p> </p><p>December 2007 1,481</p><p> </p><p>December 2008 1,550</p><p> </p><p>December 2009 1,553</p><p> </p><p>December 2010 1,503</p><p> </p><p>December 2011 1,469</p><p> </p><p>December 2012 1,401</p><p> </p><p>December 2013 1,360</p><p> </p><p>December 2014 1,327</p><p> </p><p>The figure for 2015 - 1,328 is up to and including 31st August.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p /><p> </p><p /><p> </p><p /><p> </p><p /><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-25T11:53:58.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419421/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419421/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","Shipping: Registration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many ships were on the United Kingdom register in 2005, and in each year thereafter to date.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419422","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>There are no specific plans yet.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency is currently recruiting a new Director of the UK Ship Register (UKSR) for whom an early task will be to review current regulations in light of the aspiration to grow the UKSR, and make any appropriate recommendations.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-25T11:31:11.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419422/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419422/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","Shipping: Registration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to review the regulations governing ship registration in the United Kingdom with a view to increasing the number of ships in the world fleet on the UK register without reducing standards.","false","Biography information for Lord MacKenzie of Culkein",,"Lord MacKenzie of Culkein","HL2353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419423","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-29","<p>The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, Ofwat and the Environment Agency published joint water resources management planning guidance in 2012. This included the expectation that water companies should consider all options to balance supply with demand, including water trading, cross boundary solutions and third party supplier solutions. Updated guidance is currently being prepared for publication for the next planning round.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2356","2015-09-29T11:08:34.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419423/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419423/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-17","Water Supply","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, as part of their water resource management responsibilities, water companies have been asked to look beyond their boundaries to secure sufficient water supply to satisfy future customer demand.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL2354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419424","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-01","<p>Water and sewerage companies’ responsibilities include managing the risk of flooding from surface water or sewer systems. They are also expected to work in partnership with the Environment Agency and Lead Local Flood Authorities to manage the risks of all sources of flooding within a catchment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has therefore not asked water companies to do more to co-ordinate and implement flood defences, nor is it planning to launch a tender process in the market to meet this objective.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-10-01T15:01:50.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419424/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419424/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-17","Flood Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to ask water companies to do more to co-ordinate and implement flood defences; whether they plan to launch a full and transparent tender process in the market to meet this objective; and whether water companies' work on flood defence is intended to be outwith their regulated business.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL2355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419425","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-29","<p>The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, Ofwat and the Environment Agency published joint water resources management planning guidance in 2012. This included the expectation that water companies should consider all options to balance supply with demand, including water trading, cross boundary solutions and third party supplier solutions. Updated guidance is currently being prepared for publication for the next planning round.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2354","2015-09-29T11:08:33.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419425/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419425/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-17","Water Supply","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to publish best practice guidelines as part of water resource management plans to ensure that the right solutions can be delivered at competitive prices.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL2356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419426","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-01","<p>We are currently working on finalising the legislative approach to abstraction reform. We remain on track to deliver abstraction reform in the early 2020s.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our aim is to introduce fairer, more flexible and more efficient systems to manage water abstraction tailored to differing catchments within a national approach.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-10-01T15:02:43.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419426/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419426/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-17","Water Abstraction: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to bring forward legislation for a new water abstraction licensing regime; and whether they propose to introduce a one-size-fits-all approach to reform of the sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL2357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419427","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-01","We are on track to open the non-household retail market for water and sewerage services in April 2017. All partners in the Open Water programme (the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, Ofwat and Market Operator Services Limited), are strongly committed to meeting this date. A clear timetable of the activities, which will need to be completed before the market can open, is published on Ofwat’s website and updated each month. Market Operator Services Limited is working closely with all relevant companies to ensure that they will be ready for market opening in April 2017. Incumbent water companies who want to compete in the new national retail market will need to establish a separate legal entity and apply for a Water and Sewerage Supply Licence, although they are not under any obligation to do so. Ofwat sought views on the appropriate conditions for licensees operating in the new retail market through its consultation on new Water and Sewerage Supply Licences in June 2015. It will be able to impose financial penalties on licensees who do not comply with these conditions.",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-10-01T15:02:27.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419427/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419427/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-17","Water Companies: Competition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are on target to deliver retail competition for non-household water and sewerage services in England in April 2017; whether they plan to publish a clearly defined timetable and a schedule of the trigger points necessary to meet this deadline; and whether Ofwat are able to impose financial penalties for breaches of licence conditions on companies which are not ready to become a licensee for the provision of retail services for all non-household customers by that date.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL2358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419428","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-29","<p>The Government has not planned any third party audit. We note the National Audit Office published a report in June 2014 on the risks and governance of the Thames Tideway Tunnel and may choose to write a further report. Copies of the strategic and economic case for the TTT, cost-benefit analysis and peer reviewed supporting evidence will be placed in the House Library.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In respect of contracts for new reservoirs, Ofwat have said with reference to the Thames Tideway Tunnel that it is keen to explore whether this delivery model could work for other big projects in the water sector. We are not aware of any ongoing applications to construct new reservoirs.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-09-29T11:18:40.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419428/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419428/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-17","Thames Tideway Tunnel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to commission a third-party audit of the Thames Tideway Tunnel, to be made available to assist water companies to adopt best practice when managing contracts for new reservoirs, in particular regarding the optimal use of outside contractors and specialist companies capable of constructing reservoirs.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL2359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419429","Home Office","false","2015-10-05","<p>Since 2010 Her Majesty's Government has spent £196m in Calais and the surrounding locations to secure the border, which includes day to day activity such as carrying out passport checks on all passengers, searching for illicit goods, as well as stopping and deterring illegal migration. Part of this figure includes the recent investment to reinforce security through infrastructure improvements at Border Force’s controls in Northern France. This has included £7 million for fencing at Coquelles, which will help protect Eurotunnel’s freight approach road, a £2 million upgrade of detection technology and boosting our dog searching capability by £1 million.</p><p>Her Majesty's Government is also supporting the Port of Calais to create a secure waiting area for UK-bound lorries and has committed to funding additional security guards at the Eurotunnel site in the area.</p><p>The Home Office and its partners, including the National Crime Agency, also fund wider activity to stop and deter illegal migration in Calais; however, it is not possible to attribute a specific amount to spending in the Calais area alone.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-05T16:12:06.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419429/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419429/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-17","Undocumented Migrants: Calais","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been spent since 2010 to deter illegal immigration in Calais and the surrounding region.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL2360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419430","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-29","<p>The British Government has not made any such assessment. Her Majesty’s Government of Gibraltar has constitutional competence for marine conservation and habitats in British Gibraltar Territorial Waters.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-29T16:38:16.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419430/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419430/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-17","Gibraltar: Spain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the potential benefits to marine conservation and habitats of extending British territorial waters in the sea areas around Gibraltar away from Spain.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL2361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419431","Home Office","false","2015-10-05","<p>The Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation Scheme has been running for around 18 months already, and has not involved any relaxation of the UK's immigration rules. The Prime Minister announced on 7 September an expansion of that scheme.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-05T16:01:42.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419431/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419431/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-17","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which sections of United Kingdom immigration regulations are, or will be, relaxed for Syrian refugees under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419432","Home Office","false","2015-10-05","<p>People in all immigration application routes have the potential to be granted leave to remain on compassionate grounds. There is no formal application category for ‘compassionate grounds’. The Home Office therefore cannot determine the percentage of applicants between 18 and 25 who have been granted leave to remain in the United Kingdom on compassionate grounds or how many applicants are still waiting for a decision.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-05T15:54:47.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419432/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419432/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-17","Immigration: Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the past five years, what percentage of applicants aged between 18 and 25 have been granted leave to remain in the United Kingdom on compassionate grounds; and how many applicants are still waiting for a decision.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419433","Home Office","false","2015-10-07","<p>Paragraph 276ADE(1) of the Immigration Rules sets out the requirements for leave to remain on the basis of the applicant’s private life in the UK. Under paragraph 276ADE(1)(vi), where the applicant is aged 18 or over and has lived continuously in the UK for less than 20 years (and whether or not they have done so for more than half their life), there must be “very significant obstacles” to the applicant’s integration into the country to which they would have to go if required to leave the UK. Guidance for caseworkers on this is contained in section 8.2.3.4 of the Immigration Directorate Instruction Appendix FM 1.0b Family Life (as a Partner or Parent) and Private Life: 10-Year Routes, published on GOV.UK.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-07T13:10:03.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419433/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419433/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-17","Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they define the term "very significant obstacles", as used in paragraph 276ADE(1)(vi) of the immigration rules, especially in relation to applicants who have lived in the United Kingdom for more than half their life.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419434","Home Office","false","2015-10-05","<p>We have no plans to reduce the time asylum seekers have to wait to take up employment or voluntary work. Volunteering can be undertaken at any stage of the asylum process and we support asylum seekers who engage in this positive contribution to the community, providing such activities do not amount to voluntary work or employment.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-05T16:00:38.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419434/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419434/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-17","Immigration: Appeals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to offer to those waiting in the immigration and asylum appeal process (1) the right to work after six months, and (2) an automatic right to engage in voluntary work at the beginning of the process.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419435","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-29","<p>The UK expects all EU Member States to meet their obligations to comply with international standards including with regards to the fundamental values of respect for human dignity, freedom and respect for human rights, in the same way they have this expectation of us. The British Government recognises that Hungary has received the second highest number of asylum claims of any EU Member State this year to June, reaching unprecedented levels. We continue to follow closely the situation in Hungary and other Central European countries regarding the arrival of unprecedented numbers of people seeking entry and, often, passage onwards. Staff at our Embassy in Budapest have visited the border with Serbia and reception centres and have also met with Hungarian officials. More broadly as the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), has stated, the UK and its EU partners must pursue a comprehensive approach which addresses the causes of the migration problem as well as the consequences.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-29T16:37:42.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419435/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419435/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-17","Hungary: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they plan to make to the government of Hungary about the use of tear gas and water cannon on those seeking asylum.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419436","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-24","<p>Pay policy for members of staff is the responsibility of individual fire and rescue authorities. <br><br>The Government is grateful to those members of staff who worked to ensure the safety of their communities during periods of strike action by members of the Fire Brigades Union.<br><br></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-09-24T11:54:53.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419436/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419436/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-17","Public Sector: Strikes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to change the rules for public servants so that senior public officers who work during strikes do not get extra payments, as was the case with three senior officers of the South Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Service during strikes in 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419437","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-23","<p>The United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East (UNRWA) estimates that 80,000 Palestinian refugees have left Syria since the onset of the conflict; 44,000 Palestinian refugees from Syria are confirmed in Lebanon and 15,800 are confirmed in Jordan, with the remainder in Egypt (5,000), Turkey and beyond.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-09-23T15:34:13.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419437/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419437/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-17","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of Palestinians amongst refugees fleeing Syria.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419438","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-24","<p>We have not made any representations to the Government of Israel on this issue.</p><p>The UK has pledged £1billion to date – our largest ever humanitarian response to a single crisis – to provide humanitarian assistance and long-term support to hundreds of thousands of vulnerable people living in Syria and refugees across the region, which includes Palestinian refugees who have also been affected by the crisis.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-24T15:45:05.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419438/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419438/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-17","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel concerning Israel offering refuge to Palestinians fleeing Syria.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419439","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-24","<p>We continue to be clear with both sides that there must be a just, fair and agreed settlement for refugees as part of a negotiated two-state solution. On 10 September during the visit to London of Prime Minister Netanyahu, the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), raised the need for the parties to return to negotiations.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-09-24T15:45:19.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419439/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419439/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-17","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what recent discussions they have had with the government of Israel concerning the right of return for Palestinians.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419440","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidelines on autism make it clear that families should wait no more than three months to start diagnosis. Every part of the National Health Service should be adhering to these guidelines.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are new arrangements for children and young people with special educational needs, introduced by the Children and Families Act 2014. These require clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and local authorities to make joint arrangements for ensuring a coordinated assessment of the range of eligible children’s needs, and the development of an Education, Health and Care plan to provide necessary support.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England’s Children with Complex Needs Implementation Board is leading working on ensuring robust and accountability mechanisms are in place to ensure delivery and to allow NHS England to hold CCGs to account for performance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2372","2015-09-22T13:12:54.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419440/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419440/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Autism: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans are in place to reduce the current average wait for children before a diagnosis of autism.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL2371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419441","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidelines on autism make it clear that families should wait no more than three months to start diagnosis. Every part of the National Health Service should be adhering to these guidelines.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are new arrangements for children and young people with special educational needs, introduced by the Children and Families Act 2014. These require clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and local authorities to make joint arrangements for ensuring a coordinated assessment of the range of eligible children’s needs, and the development of an Education, Health and Care plan to provide necessary support.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England’s Children with Complex Needs Implementation Board is leading working on ensuring robust and accountability mechanisms are in place to ensure delivery and to allow NHS England to hold CCGs to account for performance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2371","2015-09-22T13:12:54.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419441/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419441/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Autism: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what measures are in place to support families waiting for a diagnosis of autism for a child.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL2372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419442","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Government has taken a number of steps to support people with cerebral palsy.</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England is mandated to develop training for general practitioners to develop a special interest in the care of young people with long-term conditions. We have also funded the development of <em>Paediatric Care online</em>, a resource for supporting the clinical workforce across the full range of children’s health issues.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government funded the development of Disability Matters (launched in February 2015). This is an e-learning tool to improve the skills of anyone working to support the needs of people with a disability or complex need (of all ages), and can be used by teachers and health professionals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has introduced a new statutory framework for children and young people with special educational needs and disability, which requires clinical commissioning groups and local authorities to make joint arrangements to ensure a co-ordinated assessment of needs. The new approach will greatly improve integrated working across specialist health, education (either in mainstream or special schools), and social care, to deliver improved outcomes for the child.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no current plans to introduce a national register of children with cerebral palsy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2374 ; HL2375","2015-09-22T13:10:55.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419442/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419442/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Cerebral Palsy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to improve awareness of cerebral palsy amongst (1) medical generalists, and (2) those working in schools.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL2373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419443","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Government has taken a number of steps to support people with cerebral palsy.</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England is mandated to develop training for general practitioners to develop a special interest in the care of young people with long-term conditions. We have also funded the development of <em>Paediatric Care online</em>, a resource for supporting the clinical workforce across the full range of children’s health issues.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government funded the development of Disability Matters (launched in February 2015). This is an e-learning tool to improve the skills of anyone working to support the needs of people with a disability or complex need (of all ages), and can be used by teachers and health professionals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has introduced a new statutory framework for children and young people with special educational needs and disability, which requires clinical commissioning groups and local authorities to make joint arrangements to ensure a co-ordinated assessment of needs. The new approach will greatly improve integrated working across specialist health, education (either in mainstream or special schools), and social care, to deliver improved outcomes for the child.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no current plans to introduce a national register of children with cerebral palsy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2373 ; HL2375","2015-09-22T13:10:55.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419443/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419443/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Cerebral Palsy: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to improve access to specialist health and educational interventions for children with cerebral palsy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL2374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419444","Department of Health","false","2015-09-22","<p>The Government has taken a number of steps to support people with cerebral palsy.</p><p> </p><p>Health Education England is mandated to develop training for general practitioners to develop a special interest in the care of young people with long-term conditions. We have also funded the development of <em>Paediatric Care online</em>, a resource for supporting the clinical workforce across the full range of children’s health issues.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government funded the development of Disability Matters (launched in February 2015). This is an e-learning tool to improve the skills of anyone working to support the needs of people with a disability or complex need (of all ages), and can be used by teachers and health professionals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has introduced a new statutory framework for children and young people with special educational needs and disability, which requires clinical commissioning groups and local authorities to make joint arrangements to ensure a co-ordinated assessment of needs. The new approach will greatly improve integrated working across specialist health, education (either in mainstream or special schools), and social care, to deliver improved outcomes for the child.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no current plans to introduce a national register of children with cerebral palsy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2373 ; HL2374","2015-09-22T13:10:55.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419444/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419444/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-17","Cerebral Palsy: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to introduce a national register of children with cerebral palsy, including data on the number of children identified with the condition, and the education, health and care provision available to support those children.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL2375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419445","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-01","<p>In September 2014, at the NATO Summit, the Prime Minister announced that, &quot;the second carrier, HMS PRINCE OF WALES will also be brought into service. This will ensure that we will always have one carrier available, 100% of the time.&quot; The exact number of fixed wing aircraft embarked at any time will be dependent on the mission being undertaken.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-10-01T14:59:36.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419445/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419445/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-17","Aircraft Carriers: Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 16 September (HL1944), how many F35B Sea Lightnings were assumed to be in the air wings when the Prime Minister stated in September 2014 that both new aircrafts carriers would be operated concurrently in the future.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL2376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419446","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-28","<p>The Government has made clear in its September response to the House of Commons Defence Committee that we believe the current structure to be sufficient. The Chief of the Defence Staff attends the National Security Council with the remit to present the views of all three Services collectively. The Chiefs of Staff Committee is already the UK's senior military committee and feeds into the Chief of Defence Staff's preparation for National Security Council meetings.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-09-28T17:22:42.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419446/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419446/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-17","National Security Council: Chiefs of Staff","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the House of Commons Defence Committee's conclusion in its report <i>Decision-making in Defence Policy</i> that the Chiefs of Staff should be constituted as the Military Sub-Committee of the National Security Council.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL2377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419447","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-01","<p>The Rural Payments Agency are on track to start making payments for 2015 BPS Claims from December. The majority of these will be in December and the vast majority in January. The payment window runs from December to the end of June.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-10-01T15:00:02.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419447/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419447/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-17","Agriculture: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Rural Payments Agency will complete Basic Payment Scheme payments to eligible farmers before the end of 2015.","true","Biography information for Lord Willoughby de Broke",,"Lord Willoughby de Broke","HL2378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419448","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>The Road Investment Strategy is clear that the A303 Amesbury to Berwick Down scheme involves a tunnel of at least 1.8 miles (2.9 kilometres). Highways England is in the early stage of scheme development, looking at options, including the length of tunnel. Consultation on options will take place in 2017 and will involve stakeholders, local residents, businesses, road users and interested parties.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Highways England does not yet have reliable cost estimates for a 2.8 miles (4.5 kilometres), or 4.3 miles (7 kilometres) tunnel. This information would become available during the consideration of options. The A303/A30/A358 Corridor Feasibility Study indicated that the cost estimate for a 1.8 miles (2.9 kilometres) tunnel is in the range of £864m to £1321m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To date, Highways England has not sought funding outside of their own resources to fund a solution for the A303 past Stonehenge although this does not preclude them from considering other funding sources in the future.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2381 ; HL2382 ; HL2383","2015-09-25T11:50:48.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419448/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419448/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","A303","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to (1) investigate options, and (2) consult on proposals, to widen the A303 between Amesbury and Berwick Down following the A303/A30/A358 corridor feasibility study last year, and which organisations and individuals they plan to consult during each exercise.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419449","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>Highways England is currently in the early stage of scheme development looking at options and to date have not sought the advice of the National Committee of the International Council on Monuments and Sites.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-09-25T11:29:58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419449/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419449/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","A303","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have sought, or been given, the advice of the National Committee of the International Council on Monuments and Sites concerning proposals for dualling the A303 through the Stonehenge part of the World Heritage Site; and if so, what advice they received.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419450","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>The Road Investment Strategy is clear that the A303 Amesbury to Berwick Down scheme involves a tunnel of at least 1.8 miles (2.9 kilometres). Highways England is in the early stage of scheme development, looking at options, including the length of tunnel. Consultation on options will take place in 2017 and will involve stakeholders, local residents, businesses, road users and interested parties.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Highways England does not yet have reliable cost estimates for a 2.8 miles (4.5 kilometres), or 4.3 miles (7 kilometres) tunnel. This information would become available during the consideration of options. The A303/A30/A358 Corridor Feasibility Study indicated that the cost estimate for a 1.8 miles (2.9 kilometres) tunnel is in the range of £864m to £1321m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To date, Highways England has not sought funding outside of their own resources to fund a solution for the A303 past Stonehenge although this does not preclude them from considering other funding sources in the future.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2379 ; HL2382 ; HL2383","2015-09-25T11:50:48.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419450/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419450/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","A303","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to implement a tunnel for the A303 in order to avoid the entire surface area of the Stonehenge part of the World Heritage Site.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419451","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>The Road Investment Strategy is clear that the A303 Amesbury to Berwick Down scheme involves a tunnel of at least 1.8 miles (2.9 kilometres). Highways England is in the early stage of scheme development, looking at options, including the length of tunnel. Consultation on options will take place in 2017 and will involve stakeholders, local residents, businesses, road users and interested parties.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Highways England does not yet have reliable cost estimates for a 2.8 miles (4.5 kilometres), or 4.3 miles (7 kilometres) tunnel. This information would become available during the consideration of options. The A303/A30/A358 Corridor Feasibility Study indicated that the cost estimate for a 1.8 miles (2.9 kilometres) tunnel is in the range of £864m to £1321m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To date, Highways England has not sought funding outside of their own resources to fund a solution for the A303 past Stonehenge although this does not preclude them from considering other funding sources in the future.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2379 ; HL2381 ; HL2383","2015-09-25T11:50:48.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419451/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419451/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","A303","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the cost of a twin-bored A303 road tunnel at Stonehenge of length (1) 2.9 kilometres, (2) 4.5 kilometres, and (3) at least 7 kilometres, in order to avoid the entire surface area of the Stonehenge part of the World Heritage Site and its setting.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419452","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-25","<p>The Road Investment Strategy is clear that the A303 Amesbury to Berwick Down scheme involves a tunnel of at least 1.8 miles (2.9 kilometres). Highways England is in the early stage of scheme development, looking at options, including the length of tunnel. Consultation on options will take place in 2017 and will involve stakeholders, local residents, businesses, road users and interested parties.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Highways England does not yet have reliable cost estimates for a 2.8 miles (4.5 kilometres), or 4.3 miles (7 kilometres) tunnel. This information would become available during the consideration of options. The A303/A30/A358 Corridor Feasibility Study indicated that the cost estimate for a 1.8 miles (2.9 kilometres) tunnel is in the range of £864m to £1321m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To date, Highways England has not sought funding outside of their own resources to fund a solution for the A303 past Stonehenge although this does not preclude them from considering other funding sources in the future.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2379 ; HL2381 ; HL2382","2015-09-25T11:50:47.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419452/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419452/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-17","A303","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have sought, or intend to seek, funding outside their own resources (1) in Europe, and (2) globally, for a road-widening solution for the A303 that avoids the entire surface area of the Stonehenge part of the World Heritage Site by the use of a tunnel.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419453","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-23","<p>This Government will continue to honour its obligations under article 4 of the World Heritage Convention regarding the Stonehenge and Avebury World Heritage Site. We are<strong> </strong>committed to working with UNESCO and its advisory bodies to ensure that the Outstanding Universal Value of the World Heritage Site is taken into consideration in any forthcoming road scheme. We will be closely monitoring the development of any such scheme as it progresses.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-09-23T10:34:35.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419453/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419453/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-17","A303","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend fully to honour Article 4 of the 1972 Convention Concerning the Protection of the World’s Heritage in respect of any future A303 dualling scheme at Stonehenge; and if not, whether they intend to withdraw as a signatory to the World Heritage Convention.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL2384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419454","Attorney General","false","2015-10-12","<p>The Prime Minister gave a detailed statement on 7 September 2015 in which he informed the House that I was consulted on the action and was clear that there would be a legal basis for action in international law. By long-standing convention, reflected in the Cabinet Manual, the content of the Law Officers’ advice is not disclosed outside government without the consent of the Law Officers. As I explained in my oral evidence to the Justice Select Committee on the 15<sup>th</sup> September (<a href="http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/justice-committee/the-work-of-the-attorney-general/oral/21698.html" target="_blank">HC 409</a>), the convention should be adhered to in this case.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","10450 ; 10451 ; 10466","2015-10-12T16:19:04.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419454/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419454/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-09-17","Syria: Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, with reference to the Prime Minister's Oral Statement of 7 September 2015, Official Report, column 30, whether the legal advice provided on the targeted killing of British citizens by remote control drone in Syria covers future targeted killings of UK citizens or if new and separate advice will have to be sought for any future such killings.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","10542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419455","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Department for International Development (DFID) is responsible for assessing licence applications against Criterion 8. DFID considers export licence applications destined to all International Development Association eligible countries and may also ask to see applications in respect of other countries of concern. Further information on DFID’s role is given in the Government’s Strategic Export Controls Annual Report for 2014, which was presented to Parliament on 16 July 2015 and is also available on the gov.uk website.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-16T12:25:57.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419455/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419455/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Exports: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that criterion 8 of the consolidated EU Licensing Criteria document is consistently applied to all export licences.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","10577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419456","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-12","<p>The opaque nature of such structures means that we are unable to produce an accurate estimate of how many are used to invest corrupt money in the UK. That is one reason why the Prime Minister put beneficial ownership transparency at the heart of the UK’s G8 Presidency in 2013. The Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act received Royal Assent earlier this year and established a public register of company beneficial ownership information. This register will be operational from June 2016. The Act also abolished bearer shares and introduced a requirement for all company directors to be natural persons.</p><p>In Europe, we worked hard during the negotiation of the 4<sup>th</sup> Anti-Money Laundering Directive to encourage European partners to match our level of ambition to ensure that criminal activity would not simply be displaced. The Directive was formally adopted in June 2015 and requires all Member States to implement central registers of company beneficial ownership will access for competent authorities, obliged entities and those with a legitimate interest. Member states have until June 2017 to transpose these requirements.</p><p>The Government is continuing to take strong action to make the UK a hostile environment for corrupt money and to make it increasingly difficult for criminals to abuse corporate structures. We will shortly publish the UK’s first National Risk Assessment of Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing and have committed to publishing an Anti-Money Laundering Action Plan to address those issues which are highlighted by the National Risk Assessment.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-12T13:44:54.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419456/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419456/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of shell companies being used to invest corrupt money in the UK in each of the last 10 years; and what steps he plans to take to tighten related money laundering regulations.","false","Biography information for Stuart Blair Donaldson","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Stuart Blair Donaldson","10587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419457","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-12","<p>Land Registry has no plans to publish data on which foreign countries hold land and property titles in England and Wales.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-12T14:00:00.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419457/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419457/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Land: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he expects the Land Registry to publish data on which foreign countries own which land property titles in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Stuart Blair Donaldson","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Stuart Blair Donaldson","10588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419458","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-12","<p>The Prime Minister stated during a speech made in Singapore on 28 July that he will consult on the best way forward to extending what we ask of UK companies to foreign companies.</p><p>He has also asked Land Registry from this autumn to publish data on which foreign companies own which land and property titles in England and Wales.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-12T14:01:27.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419458/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419458/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Foreign Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps the Government has taken to make property ownership by foreign companies more transparent.","false","Biography information for Stuart Blair Donaldson","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Stuart Blair Donaldson","10590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419459","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-12","<p>From next year companies registered in the UK will be required to hold a register of people with significant influence or control over them. This information will be filed with Companies House, which will maintain a central, publicly accessible register.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-12T12:24:30.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419459/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419459/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps the Government is taking to reform company law to require the disclosure of beneficial controlling interests of offshore companies.","false","Biography information for Stuart Blair Donaldson","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Stuart Blair Donaldson","10589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419460","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-16","<p>The paper referred to provides interim research results on potential pregnancy and maternity-related discrimination and disadvantage in the workplace. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, in collaboration with the Equality and Human Rights Commission, is undertaking further analysis, to be published later this year, which may include some financial information, where estimates are possible.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-16T12:31:01.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419460/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419460/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Gender: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to his Department's Research Paper No. 235, on pregnancy and maternity-related discrimination and disadvantages, what estimate his Department has made of the annual cost to the economy of women forced out of work on account of their pregnancy or maternity leave.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","10656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419461","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-16","<p>Trade unions have a constructive role to play in maintaining positive industrial relations. The British Social Attitudes Survey and the Workplace Employment Relations Survey provide information on how the population, employers and union members view the services and activities of Trade Unions. The Office for National Statistics publishes estimates of the approximate Gross Added Value for Trade Union activities as well as the number of disputes (and days lost to industrial action).</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-16T12:29:56.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419461/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419461/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-17","Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the contribution of trades unions to the national economy.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","10638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419462","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-14","<p>There are no plans to require restaurants and take-away food outlets to specify the fish species being offered for sale. However this information should be available to the owners or managers of these establishments, so they could let their customers know which fish they are buying if they are asked.</p><p>The general provisions of the Food Safety Act 1990, General Food Law Regulation 178/2002, and the Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008 make it an offence to label or present food in a false or misleading way. A failure to adequately describe or label fish species in a food may constitute an offence under these rules.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-14T14:01:41.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419462/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419462/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-17","Fish","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will require restaurants and take-away food outlets selling meals described as fish to specify the species of fish the dish contains.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","10598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419463","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-12","<p>Government will account for its costs at the end of the Inquiry.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-12T16:47:12.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419463/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419463/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-17","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September 2015 to Question 9949, what the (a) total number of working hours Government lawyers have spent advising recipients of Salmon Letters in the Iraq Inquiry and (b) cost to the public purse of that advice is.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","10583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419464","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-12","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-10-12T16:44:58.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419464/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419464/answer","PQ figures_final.xlsx ; 10660 FINAL.pdf","PQ figures_final.xlsx ; 10660 FINAL.pdf","Excel Attachment for Member ; UKSA Letter for Member ","Excel Attachment for Member ; UKSA Letter for Member ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419464/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-17","Teenage Pregnancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of (a) teenage, (b) 15 year old, (c) 16 year old and (d) 17 year old girls (i) became pregnant and (ii) gave birth in each local authority area in the most recent three-year period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","10660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419465","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>The information requested is available on the Financial Conduct Authority’s website:</p><p><a href="http://www.fca.org.uk/consumers/financial-services-products/banking/interest-rate-hedging-products" target="_blank">http://www.fca.org.uk/consumers/financial-services-products/banking/interest-rate-hedging-products</a>.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-16T13:29:50.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419465/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419465/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Interest Rate Swap Transactions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the interest rate hedging products redress scheme operated by the Financial Conduct Authority.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","10547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419466","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-12","<p>In view of the situation in Syria, Council Regulation (EU) No 36/2012 of 18 January 2012 imposed an asset freeze against listed Syrian individuals and entities. The EU Regulation, which has direct effect in the UK, requires that all funds and economic resources belonging to, owned, held or controlled by listed persons are frozen.</p><p>Those listed under this regime include natural and legal persons, entities and bodies who have been identified as being responsible for the violent repression against the civilian population in Syria, persons and entities benefiting from or supporting the regime, and natural or legal persons associated with them. These persons and entities include, but are not limited to, President Assad and several members and agencies of the Syrian government.</p><p>The approximate aggregate value of funds frozen in UK jurisdiction under EU Regulation 36/2012 is £151,080,000 (based on an annual audit in September 2014). These funds continue to belong to the individuals and entities listed under the Regulation and are not seized or otherwise held by HM Government.</p><p>The Regulation states that HM Treasury can use this information only for the purpose for which it was provided. In order to comply with this requirement, and to comply with UK data protection law, the figure is provided on an aggregate basis so as not to disclose data relating to funds held by particular individuals or entities.</p><p>HM Treasury publishes the names of those subject to EU financial sanctions on the Consolidated List of Financial Sanctions Targets in the UK, which can be found on the gov.uk website.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-12T13:42:04.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419466/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419466/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Freezing of Assets: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assets of (a) President Assad and (b) the Syrian government have been frozen in the UK; and what the value is of those assets.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","10552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419467","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not collect data on VAT receipts from particular goods and services, and has not estimated the VAT take from tourism businesses in Wales.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-16T13:47:57.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419467/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419467/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Tourism: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the annual VAT take is from tourism businesses in Wales.","false","Biography information for Dr James Davies","Vale of Clwyd","Dr James Davies","10571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419468","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-12","<p>There are no taxes levied specifically on open cast coal mining. This activity is subject to the UK's general taxation regimes such as VAT and Corporation Tax. However it is not possible to say how much revenue these taxes raise from open cast mines, as the number of companies involved is below the Government’s threshold for disclosing tax liabilities.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-12T14:05:17.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419468/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419468/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Opencast Mining: Tax Yields","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has accrued to the public purse in tax receipts from the extraction of coal from open cast mines over the period 1995 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","10607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419469","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>Environmental protection is a devolved matter, and outstanding land restoration liabilities lie with the relevant local authorities and ultimately with the Scottish Government. The Treasury has fully considered the two proposals put to them for addressing the shortfall of land restoration on abandoned Scottish coal mines: an exemption from the Carbon Price Support (CPS) tax and a direct grant from the Exchequer. Following discussions with Hargreaves, the UK Coal Authority, the Scotland Office, the Scottish Government and DECC, the Treasury has had to decline both proposals after thorough consideration. The reasons for this include: - Addressing the shortfall in land restoration is not the responsibility of the UK Government. Environmental protection is a devolved matter, and outstanding land restoration liabilities lie with the relevant local authorities. - The proposals are unaffordable in the current fiscal climate. They would also set a precedent that would risk discouraging companies and local authorities from making proper financial provision for the cost of site restoration and future environmental liabilities. - A CPS exemption would be an inefficient means of addressing the shortfall of land restoration, as the money would not go directly towards this aim and it would incur significant administration costs. - A CPS exemption would distort the market by making non-exempt coal less competitive, and by discouraging investment in low carbon power generation. I have written to the Scottish Government’s Minister for Business, Energy and Tourism informing him of this decision and I would be happy to consider any other options put forward.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","10601 ; 10603 ; 10604 ; 10606 ; 10608 ; 10609 ; 10610 ; 10611 ; 10612 ; 10615 ; 11469","2015-10-21T13:33:15.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419469/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419469/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-17","Carbon Emissions: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of (a) the merits and (b) compatibility with European requirements of a carbon price support exemption scheme in Scotland; and by what process evaluation of that scheme was conducted.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","10605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419470","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>Environmental protection is a devolved matter, and outstanding land restoration liabilities lie with the relevant local authorities and ultimately with the Scottish Government. The Treasury has fully considered the two proposals put to them for addressing the shortfall of land restoration on abandoned Scottish coal mines: an exemption from the Carbon Price Support (CPS) tax and a direct grant from the Exchequer. Following discussions with Hargreaves, the UK Coal Authority, the Scotland Office, the Scottish Government and DECC, the Treasury has had to decline both proposals after thorough consideration. The reasons for this include: - Addressing the shortfall in land restoration is not the responsibility of the UK Government. Environmental protection is a devolved matter, and outstanding land restoration liabilities lie with the relevant local authorities. - The proposals are unaffordable in the current fiscal climate. They would also set a precedent that would risk discouraging companies and local authorities from making proper financial provision for the cost of site restoration and future environmental liabilities. - A CPS exemption would be an inefficient means of addressing the shortfall of land restoration, as the money would not go directly towards this aim and it would incur significant administration costs. - A CPS exemption would distort the market by making non-exempt coal less competitive, and by discouraging investment in low carbon power generation. I have written to the Scottish Government’s Minister for Business, Energy and Tourism informing him of this decision and I would be happy to consider any other options put forward.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","10601 ; 10603 ; 10604 ; 10605 ; 10608 ; 10609 ; 10610 ; 10611 ; 10612 ; 10615 ; 11469","2015-10-21T13:33:15.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/419470/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","